" Colemak remappings; use backspace for left
" Borrows from:
" * http://colemak.com/pub/vim/colemak.vim
" * http://colemak.com/forum/viewtopic.php?id=50
" 
" Instead of hjkl for ←↓↑→, use jkhl (QWERTY ynhu)
" While it doesn't keep navigation on the home row, it does use the same
" keys as standard vim navigation, to avoid mapping conflicts, and it
" makes spatial sense:
"   QWERTY h/n are vertical for up/down
"   QWERTY y/u are horizontal for left/right
"
noremap h k
noremap k j
noremap j h

" Turbo navigation mode
" Modified to work with counts, see :help complex-repeat
nnoremap <silent> J @='5j'<CR>|xnoremap <silent> N @='5j'<CR>|onoremap J 5h|
nnoremap <silent> H @='5h'<CR>|xnoremap <silent> U @='5h'<CR>|onoremap H 5k|
nnoremap <silent> K @='5k'<CR>|xnoremap <silent> E @='5k'<CR>|onoremap K 5j|
nnoremap <silent> L @='5l'<CR>|xnoremap <silent> I @='5l'<CR>|onoremap L 5l|
inoremap <M-J> <C-o>5j|cnoremap <M-J> <Left><Left><Left><Left><Left>|
inoremap <M-H> <C-o>5h|cnoremap <M-H> <Up><Up><Up><Up><Up>|
inoremap <M-K> <C-o>5k|cnoremap <M-K> <Down><Down><Down><Down><Down>|
inoremap <M-L> <C-o>5l|cnoremap <M-L> <Right><Right><Right><Right><Right>|

" Use the command key with navigation keys to move through displayed lines
" The default navigation is only for numbered lines, which can be disorienting with line wrapping
vmap <D-j> gh
vmap <D-k> gj
vmap <D-4> g$
vmap <D-6> g^
vmap <D-0> g^
nmap <D-j> gh
nmap <D-k> gj
nmap <D-4> g$
nmap <D-6> g^
nmap <D-0> g^

" Remap window navigation
noremap <C-w>h <C-w>k
noremap <C-W>H <C-W>K
noremap <C-w>k <C-w>j
noremap <C-W>K <C-W>J
noremap <C-w>j <C-w>h
noremap <C-W>J <C-W>H

" Remap horizontal scroll options
noremap zh zj
noremap zH zJ

" Remap fold options
noremap zj zk
noremap zk zh

